item.title: Prabowo Subianto takes oath as eighth president of Indonesia
item.description: Prabowo Subianto, sworn in as Indonesia's eighth president on Sunday, took his oath on the Quran in Jakarta. The ceremony saw attendance from global leaders and supporters. Subianto, a former defense minister and rival to ex-President Widodo, promises continuity of existing policies.

item.title: Victorian premier pushes ahead with housing plan to rezone affluent areas despite anger from locals
item.description:
Brighton residents chanted ‘shame, premier, shame’ as they surrounded the pub where Jacinta Allan announced the policy

Victoria’s premier has taken aim at opponents of government plans for high-rise apartments to soar above Melbourne’s inner suburbs.

Jacinta Allan on Sunday announced a plan to create 50 new “activity zones” to help deliver more than 30,000 additional homes across Melbourne by 2051.

item.title: Israeli strike on Gaza multi-storey residential building reportedly kills dozens
item.description:
At least 73 people died in the strike, doctors and officials say; Israeli army disputes casualty numbers and says attack was directed at a Hamas target

An Israeli airstrike that hit several houses and a multi-storey residential building in the town of Beit Lahiya in northern Gaza caused dozens of casualties, doctors and officials said.

The Hamas media office said at least 73 people had been killed in the strike on Saturday. No official figures were immediately available from the health ministry, however Medway Abbas, a senior health ministry official, said the figures were accurate.

item.title: Is China cannibalising the EU car industry?
item.description:
Troubles at VW point to growing doubts about future of Europe-wide sector as imports of cheap EVs rise

For decades Germany has enjoyed a reputation as Europe’s car capital, with slogans such as Vorsprung durch Technik emblematic of its political and industrial prowess.

But troubles looming over Volkswagen, where unions are battling threats of layoffs and factory closures, have raised questions not just about its future but the wider European car industry.
